{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_ambrosia_ver01/data/sn83045774/00271744134/1921021301/0402.xml":{"full_text":"4\n8\nRailroad\nPossibilities of Highe\nEfficiency at Vastl\nLower Costs Tun\nTrend Toward Gen\neral Adoption o\nElectric Power\nBy WILLIAM J. KEARY.\nMAX has been continually striving\nreduce costs either through the ii\nventlon and application of betti\ninstruments of production or through a mo\nscientific organization and administration\nto/Inotrif He t V, inn/^Anmr r\\f rvio? rx ..fill\nnew discoveries for the comfort and co\nvenience of the community, or for more e\nflclent and less expensive methods of pr\nduction, nothing affords a better ijlustratk\nthan the development of electricity. In i\nearly stages we find it in use in telegraph\ncommunication, furnishing the meat\nwhereby nations could know one anothi\nmore intimately through more facile ar\nrffpid communication. Later we -find it belr\nemployed for lighting purposes, and in rap\nsuccession followed its use for traction, 1\nthe telephone and in wireless telegraph;\nYet authorities agree that we are only 1\nthe dawn of an electrical age.\nOne of the most interesting phases of tf\napplication of electricity is its gradual dli\nplacement of steam as the motive power\ntransportation. It required the condition\ncreated by the war and the experience of\nbitterly cold winter during that period t\ndemonstrate the relative superiority of th\nelectrically operated road' over the steal\nroad. Prior to that time the advantages\nelectrical traction for city and suburba\ntraffic were generally recognized, but it\neconomy, and adaptability to transportatio\ngenerally were not widely appreciated 1\nwas proven that the traffic congestion tha\narose from the movement of vast supplie\nof war munitions and large bodies of troop\ncould have been entirely avoided or greatl\nminimized if the right of way had bee\nelectrified. Trains with great carrying ce\npacity were moved more speedily and regu\n;rly on electric divisions. Protracted spell\n>f zero weather which blocked or reduce\nie effectiveness of the steam locomotiv\nd no similar harmful results on the elec\nto locomotive.\nVast Saving in Fuel Costs\nPromised by Electribcatio\nIn considering the advantages of electrlfl\nv cation the first favorable argument, althoug\nprobably not the most Important, that pre\nsents itself is the saving in fuel costs tha\nwould bo effected. Total production of cot\nin the United States in 1916 was approx:\nmately 678,000,000 tons, of which the steat\nrailroads used 163,000,000 tons, or 24 pe\ncent. In addition to the coal the railroad\nA C AAA AAA hneral. ~?1\nabout 13,000,000 tons of coal, making- a tott\ncoal equivalent of 176,000,000 tons.\nA well known engineer has estimated, usln\nas his basis two and one-half pounds of coa\nas the equivalent of one kilowatt hour, tha\nby running the railroads of the country b;\nelectricity generated exclusively from fu?\nover 130,000,000 tons of coal would be save\nannually to tho nation. Valuing this savin\ncommercially at present day prices of coa\nIt represents nearly $1,000,000,000 annuall>\nor about 20 per cent, of the total operat\ning expenses of the roads. The St. Pau\nRailroad, which Is the leading exponent o\nelectrification, with over 650 miles of It\nKeen Eco\n\nIN addition to the prizes for The Ne\nYork Herald Civics Essay Contest, ar\nnounced last Sunday, it was decided I\naward two honorable mentions for othf\nmanuscripts.\nThose who have received that dlstlnctio\nat the hands of the Judges are Samu<\nCharry, who, as was the winner of the flr!\nprlee, Arnott J. White, was graduated froi\nthe Commercial High School, while anothe\nhonorable mention went to the De Wli\nClinton High School, represented In this ir\nstance by Morton Roth.\nAlthough the contest was open to sti\ndents In the fourth year of the high school\nof New York city only, its theme, \"In Vie\nof the Present Industrial Conditions and Sc\neial Unrest, What Are the Obligations It\ncumbent Upon the American Cltitzen?\" ai\ntractcd wide attention. One of the most ai\ntractive manuscripts was received from\nstudent of the Marymount Academy at Tai\nrytown. while from Montclair, N. J? cam\nan equally interesting contribution, which i\nherewith printed.\nA letter of acknowledgment has been re\nreived from I ho winner of the second prlz*\nMiss Helen* Hartung of the Kvander Child\nHigh School, which is as follows:\n\"It (rave me irreat pleasure. Indeed, to r?\ncelve the second prize for the essay I ser\nyou lately from Mr. Harrington on Monda\nevening. and I herewith wish to express m\nthanks to the judges nf the contest.\n\"I think that by fostering and aiding th\ngrowth of true Americanism through th'\ncontest Thk New York Herald has agai\nshown Its customary nplrlt of loyalty an\nhelpfulness to this country In a very fln\nway.\"\nMorton Roth's essay Is given herewith, am\nthe one by Samuel Charry will appear In ai\nearly Issue of the Sunday Magazine sectior\nBy MORTON ROTH\nCONFRONTED by many problems, th\nAmerican nation turns about, be\nwildered, hoping for a speedy am\ncomplete solution to these problems, ye\nrealizing fully that It must undergo seyern\nordeals before It can feel secure again. Afte\nall, ths bsst way to learn la by experience\nthe American nation especially seems ti\nlearn best by experience Refore castini\nabout for the best means for solving ou\nproblem, let us state carefully the exue\n\n7 TH\nElectrifk\nIn upper panel, ore train on th\nlocomotives, and freight train on t\nFalls dam in the Missouri at Vo\ny\nV.y.vXy.\nto ,<^ap\n~n i <Sp%,\nBr\nof\nf i\nSS&&-..C.;: :i/' Vi'\n16 track electrified, in one year saved over\n9- 500,000 tons of coal and 250,000 barrels of\n^f fuel oil.\nmiuuiei ictuiur in me luei sn.uauon is tne\nsubstantial economy that would be effected\na through the elimination of the necessity for\no hauling coal for railroad purposes. About\nie 20 per cent, of the total freight haulage\nof the roads consists of coal needed for their\nown use. The coal is hauled from the mine\n)f to the coaling station; it is hauled from the\nn coaling station in the tender of the locomos\ntive, and the empty car is again hauled to\nthe colliery. Electrical operation would\nmake this extensive carrying movement unt\nnecessary, and thereby add 20 per cent,\nto the freight revenues of the carriers, in\naddition to supplying greater equipment ac'\ncommodation to the business of the nation.\nn Transportation Facilities Fail\nTo Meet Normal Requirements\ns Traffic congestion has not vanished with\nd the exigencies of war. Since 1914 our busie\nness and Industries have expanded tremeni\ndously, and as our railroad facilities for\nvarious reasons failed to keep pace with our\ncommercial growth our equipment is Inadequate\nto cope with normal business requiren\nments.\nIt is admitted that with the continued\nI\" expansion in our industry not only will\nh more equipment be required but that means\ni- must be found for moving a greater volume\nn or iramc tnan existing facilities will acil\ncommodate in order to avoid the frel*\nquent tleups that would be otherwise In-\nn evltable. This could be accomplished through\nt the laying of additional trackage, but at\nIs prohibitive expense, owing to the new rights\no of way that in many instances would have\nil to be acquired, the new tunnelling that would j\nhave to be done and other difficulties that\nK would be encountered. The object, however,\nd can be achieved equally well by electriflca-\nt tion, and taking into account the other great i\ny economies to be derived frohi this procedure i\nsi it seems the logical method of increasing 1\nd our transit capacity. I\ng This is made possible by the fact that\n1. the electric locomotive can haul longer i\ntrains at higher speed. Steam locomotives i\nhave a maximum of about 3,000 horse 1\nil power, whereas there are a number of i\nf electric locomotives in use having a\ns capacity of 4,000 horse power and over. An\nnomics Ana\nw\no Morton Roth's Manuscri\nContest, Sets Forth L\n'i While Restrici\nit\nn problems and closely examine their nature,\nir We are' now In a period of transition,\ntt The period began with the signing of the\ni- armistice with Germany In November, 1918.\nand, according to all Indications and In the\ni- opinion of most experts, will terminate some\nIs time around the end of the spring of this\nw year.\n>i\nSolving the Complex Problem\nOf Returning to Peace Basis\na To he more specific, It is a period In which\nour Industrial forces will have to turn their\na energy from the manufacture of war m?1s\nterlal to the manufacture of peace time material;\na period during which the seller will\nhave to lower his prices; a period during\nb, which the laborer will have to become accuss\nturned to lower wages; a period during which\nthe people of all classes will have to learn\nanew the habits of wlae spending and forit\nget the wasteful extravagance practised\nV ilnrinir nnri lmrrn?dlnl#>lv uftnr t h*? wqv\ny period during which Instead of having Its\nemotions of patriotism and loyalty brought j\n10 to the fore by the Government, the American\npeople will have Its emotions of class war-\nn fare?who knows, hatred??and dlssatlsfac''\ntlon with the Government itself brought out\nIn Its most malignant forms.\nTo pass through this period safely and\n1 with a minimum of trouble Is the problem\nn whloh confronts the American people, and It\nis the solution of this problem that wo are\nto study with the object of determining how\nthe American citizen, and all who reside\n0 here, for that matter, can best help to solve.\nr Truly a complex problem?but the method\nd of solution is comparatively simple when we\nt examine It.\ntl It Is Indeed a strange thing that It takes\nr so very little time for our country to get on\na war basis but It takes so long a time to\ni) get back on a peace basis. Rome of these\nproblems hnvo already been solved. The\nr manufacture of war malerlal, with the ext\nceplion of the carrying out of our naval i\nE NEW YORK HERALD,\nnation CM\nle Butte, Anaconda and Pacific haul\nhe St. Paul hauled by one 3,000 V.\nlta for the 60.000 kw. station of tl\ni\nj?:i?\n\ni\nI ^^HzSH^^H\nI\n?i ^^^Mi^rii^TiTnliMiMHl^B\n,frt4. jw\" ^5\nIfiif\n.'.X\nI lli ^mi-' '\"iingrr aaeasi\nIlluminating example is furnished by th*\n:ase of the Norfolk and Western Railway\nwhich serves an important coal field in Wesi\nVirginia. As the output of coal in the vicinity\nincreased, the facilities of the railroad\nwere taxed to the utmost in keeping\npace with the growing demands made on it\nfor increased transportation, until a physcal\nlimit was reached. On examining th?\nsituation it was found that freight moved\nfreely all along its line except on a portion\nthirty miles in length on a very stlfl\n(trade. Three of the largest steam locomotives\ncould not move, traffic in this section\niny faster than seven miles an hour, and\nis a result there was congestion on the entire\nroute. Electrification solved the diffl:ulty,\nand now huge electric locomotives\nhaul heavier trains up the grade at a speed\nof fourteen miles an hour. In this mannei\nlysis in Es\nipt, One of Close Rival;\n)uties of Citizenship in\nted to City's High Scl\nprogramme, has ceased; but the return tc\nthe manufacture of material for use during\npeace time has not proceeded so satisfactorily.\nStatistics for the year 1920 are no!\nyet available, but It Is certain that there\nwere a great-many more failures during that\nyear than during the preceding year. Estimates\nof the unemployment during December,\n1920, and January, 1921, range from less\nthan one million to more than two million\nunemployed, so that even the more conservative\nestimates show thaj the employment\nconditions are appalling.\nThis business depression, which began last\nApril, is existing throughout all sections ot\nthe country. In the West the farmers ar*\nlosing vast sums of money; In the South the\n?otton growers are left with their crops on\ntheir hands: In the North manufacturing\nhas been cut down greatly and has In some\nases entirely censed. Some of the manufacturers\nhave offered the workers ihelr\nVw ti on? ak/^tU 1\niivfivt ir-^tt' v.i i iiuiii n inul irns pity\nind a complete shutting down of the plant.\nThe w< rker* have In moat case* chosen the\nleaner of the evil*.\nRetailers Among the Last\nTo Conform to New Conditions\nUnfortunately the eeller?the middleman\n!>r retailer?ha* not taken steps to return\nto a peace hast*. Retail price* are undoubtedly\nlower than they were during the war,\nDUt tney have not come down enough. We\nannot hope to have pre-war price*, but It\na certain that price* will be reduced greatly\nn the near future. Fortunately, the Amercan\npeople are leaving behind their wartime\nwasteful extravagance and are practicing\nthrift. Of courae the American* were thrifty\nluring the war, an the records of the *ale\n>f Liberty bond* and war saving* stamps\n(how, but the record* also show too clearly\nthat the extravagance more than equalized\nthe thrift.\nPerhaps the most difficult problem is the\nittltude of mind that the public assumes.\nSUNDAY, FEBRUARY 13,\nEfers Way\ned by two eighty ton 2,400 V. D. C.\nD. C. locomotive. Below, the Great\nlie St. Paul.\nvv...-yy-> v .-...-.w\nm/mmt m&tmx; p\ni\n\"&<W!gL A,\\\najjpjR.\nm\n\nmm\nW\nthe capacity of the system has been in- w\ncreased over 100 per cent. s;\nt In comparing the relative merits of the g\nsteam and electric locomotive the latter p\nstands out conspicuously superior in prac- tl\ntlcally every respect. Perhaps the greatest si\nt drawback of the steam locomotive is Its a\nwastefulness. Whether the flres are banked pi\nin the roundhouse and being cleaned for p.\nI starting, or the engine is coasting on down\ni grade or standing -on the tracks, fuel Is w\nI being consumed without any useful work t<\nbeing done. Kstimates place the quantity\nof coal wasted In this manner at one-third E\nI of the total used by the roads. jo\nContrasted with this the electric loco- el\nmotive is not only devoid of uneconomical c\ni tendencies of a like nature, but In coasting w\n1 down grades actually returns power to 'he o\nsystem through the use of regenerator cl\npniT XUi n\naqy .mining\ns of Prize Winners in T1\nClear and Forceful W;\n100I, Stirs Interest in Ou\ni These are Indeed times that try men's souls. 11\nMen are everywhere advocating change? tl\nchange in government, change In social con- si\ndltlons, change In the economic and Indus- p<\ntrial order. As time progresses change must\ncome about. Every period of the world's tl\nhistory is a period of transition?If not of bi\nprogression, then of regression?but a BJ:\nchange is always coming about. It is lrre- cf\nsistlble and hence Inevitable. Customs have\nchanged, scientific views have changed, re- )r\nllglous views have changed, government has\nchanged, Industrial methods have changed,\nliving conditions have changed; all these\nhn.n ore nnnota nfl8?\n?J\nchanges, some not as noticeably as others,\nbut nevertheless undergoing a change clearly v(\nperceptible to the careful observer. At this\ntime we have Socialists and various radicals fc\nin our midst who are advocating change of 01\ngovernment and the social and economic\norder. Dissatisfied with conditions, they ask\nfor reform, as Is their privilege and right,\nand they work to further their ends, some er\nadopting a more conservative, others a more of\nradical, course. Of these reformers we shall tt\nhear more later. Ir\nThese, then, are the various phases of the m\nproblem. The American people have the ,n\nI power of determining how this period shall wi\nbo traversed, whether It shall be one of In- H|\ndustrlal strife and social upheavals or one (J\nIn which wise counsel will prevail and In\nwhich peace will exist. Retter and more\nprosperous times will come, but before they\narrive this norlorl must he nnnsed onit It la tW\nthe duty of every American to make things\nas easy as possible. to\nHut what are these things which we Oi\nAmericans ought to do In order to make P\"\nthis period of transition easier? Are we fr\nto submit to unfair prices and unjust rents? It\nAre we to view with complacency alleged th\ncorruption In pur loog,l government? Is the re\ngeneral public to suffer forever because Of P?\nthe fights of labor and capital? Is It to be of\nexpected that capital will submit catynly and pit\ntake orders from the workers? Ts labor to ce\ncease Its agitation for better wages and\n4\nL921.\nto Save\nHundreds of Miles of Ele<\nOperating Prove Ad\\\nProjects Plann\nbrakes and saves the equipment from the trc\n-acking that the wear of airbrakes on de- loc\nscents entails. In freezing temperatures the ve\npower of the steam engine is reduced, re- mi\nsuiting frequently In paralysis of trattic, thi\nwhile in snow blockades additional difficulty\ns experienced in getting coal and water, tri\n3n the St. Paul in the winter of 1917-1918 wa\nt was a frequent occurrence to make up on be<\nhe 450 miles of line then electrified the bl>\nlours lost by trains on the adjacent steam poi\n>perated sections of the track; tra\nThe estimate of fuel saving did not take po'\nnto account our great undeveloped water sta\njower resources, the proper utilization of ro?\nvhioh would add considerably to the esti-\nnateci economy. According to the geologi- th?\n:al survey the undeveloped water power of tra\nhe United States is approximately equiva- fro\nent to 54,000,000 horse-power, of which wh\n13 per cent. Is in the mountain States, 30 per wa\nsent, in the Pacific States, and the remainder pjij\ns distributed in Eastern, Southern and inidand\n8tates. The fact that only about 10,- Im\n(00,000 horse-power'of this vast potential\nsapacity has been developed emphasizes our\nleglect of this extremely important and cco-\nlomieal source of energy. to\nRecent developments, however, indicate rUi\nhat we are at last conscious of the possi- aja\nunties tnat lie in tnis direction, xt is pro- t.101\n>osed by engineers to link up steam and jec\nvis\np?r\nli an<\nad<\ni am\npla\nto\nI\non\n(net'\nWOl\nWO I\nrater power plants in great connected trunk mel\nystems along similar lines to those of the 8nu\nrouplng of the railroads. Already an ap- b?\nropriatlon has been asked of Congress tor sol<\nle purpose of making a survey of intra- ne8\ntate system, linking up Boston, New York T\nnd Washington by combining the existing mui\nlants and adding the undeveloped water has\nower. bull\nThe latent energy of our flowing water for\nrould in itself furnish the necessary force wltl\n3 run all our railroads by electricity if it antl\nould be all cheaply and easily employed, trtfl\nlut there will necessarily be a percentage met\nf it that It will not be practicable to utilize to 1\nIther because of location, engineering difll- dec)\nulties or other reasons of weight, so that trai\nrater and coal must supplement one an- elec\nther in the generation of power. Efll- tha\nlency dictates that the coal, Instead of being will\nr Hnnnrsihlf\nJail\nie New York Herald\nthe\nay Competition, i?8?t\ntside Places\npos<\nvlng: conditions? Is submission, after all,\nle spirit of Americanism? Is cowardly\njbmlssion the panacea for the evils of this\nactl\nsriod?\nThe keynote to the answers to these ques- or^j\nons is that the spirit, not of submission, aJar\nit of cooperation must prevail. The same\n>irlt that carried us through the war can\nwry us through this- comparatively brief\nsriod after the war. Certain obligations are r a\nicumbent upon ail members of our society,\nipeclally American citizens, who are\nedged to support their Government; if the\n>irit of cooperation prevails, that is, if fP.\nrery one fulfils the obligations tfhlch de-\nslve upon him, then we shall safely pass 8 r\nirough this period and be little the worse J*11\"\n>r our experience; but If all do not co- 808\n>erate we shall have a much harder time ,)rnl\nIt. our\nWe must have cooperation betwben laborer n\nid employer. Both the laborer and the e\nnployer must adopt a common sense view K'\"'\nconditions and must have a regard for\nle rights of each other and of the public. terc\nistead of bejng guided by passions they hav\nust consider the economic forces Involved ^av\nihelr disputes and act accordingly. What ,,on\no need in America Is less business in re\npon ana more reunion in Dusiness.\nrges Constant Guard Against J\nAH Undemocratic Agencies pub\nWe must likewise have cooperation be- gov*\nreen our various governmental rlepart- opei\nenta, and petty quarrels must be eliminated wltl\nthe end thnt the public be beat served.\na the other hand, the public must have whli\nitlence, and If Investigations into alleged will\naud and corruption are being conducted vall\nmust carefully weigh the evidence and com\nen Judge Instead of condemning without we\nason. Too often do we ph.* up our news- has!\nipers and after reading a garbled account hart\nsome Investigation throw down the news- unit\niper. disgusted, and conclude that all con- we 1\nrned Investlgntnrs and Investigated alike last\nare crooked and should be locked up in be I\nBillions\n:trified Lines Already\nantages?Similar\ned Abroad\ninsported to various destinations for the\nral productiou of power, should bo con\nrted into energy near the mouth of the\nnes, and the power served long distances\nrough transmission lines.\nMost of the energy for the St. Paul elecfication\nis furnished by the rushing\n.ters of the Missouri River, which have\n?n dammed in a number of places, nota\nGreat Falls. Power generated at these\nInts is distributed hundreds of miles by\nnsmlssion lines, and supplemented by\nwer generated from other hydro-electric\n.tlons further distant, furnishes the railid\nwith a continuous supply of energy.\nIt is Interesting to note that the force\nit drives the great electrically hauled\n.ins over the majestic Rockies is drawn\nm the surrounding rivers and streams\nilch for thousands of years have been\nsting a power that could have accomshed\nmuch useful work for man.\nMerest in Electrification\nStirs European Countries\nnterest in electrification is not confined\nthe United States, but is general in Eulean\ncountries. Confronted with an\nrming scarcity of coal, the different nans\nhave been obliged to consider the subt\nseriously. Recently a French mission\nited this country with the object of reding\nwhat progress had been made here\nthe matter and of examining the means\n1 methods employed, with a view to their\n>ption in France. Switzerland has a very\nbltlous programme. The authorities are\nnning to electrify all the Government\nned lines in the country, spreading the\nrk over a period of twenty years. Switzmd\nis particularly favored because of\ngreat potential power in its mountain\nearns and torrents, and the plans out?d\nshow that its business heads are alive\nthe possibilities.\ntaly, which is almost totally dependent\noutside sources for its coal, realizes the\nessity of conserving its fuel supply and\nproceeding with plans for the electriflca1\nof its roads. According to recent ad8S,\nLenine is advocating the elertriflca1\nof all the railroads of Russia and urging\nfullest utilization of its water poweir\nources.\ntrazil is at present electrifying a portion\nIts steam roads for a distance of twentyht\nmiles, with a total of seventy-flve miles\ntrack, so that it is evident that the trend\nrard electrification is worldwide, a fact\nt confirms the claims of superiority made\nit.\nn so far as the scrapping of equipment\nconcerned, the extent of it and the retant\nloss would be very slight. Electrifllon\nis a process that cannot be performed\ni day?it must be done gradually. As dVie\ntlon of the line is electrified the steam\nimotives can be used on the other amis,\nand as all new equipment ordered\nild be electrical, by the time the road\nild be wholly electrified the steam equlpnt\nwould have become increasingly\ngler through wear or usage. It may\ncorrectly stated that the loss from ob scenoe\nwould be so small as to be\nliable.\nhe world is progressing, and our railroads\nst progress with It. Steam locomotion\nplayed a big role In the development and\nding up of the country and Its industries,\nwhich it must receive due credit, but\nh the advance of science It is becoming\niquated. With the possibilities In elecicatlon\nbecoming more widely appreciated\n1 with foresight and courage will be found\nmake .its application general. The next\nade will witness great strides in the\nisformation of our roads from sjeam to\nitrical equipment. It is a safe prediction\nt two decades from now the steam engine\nbe fast fading into past history.\nMention\nWe must be careful and patient In all\nh matters.\nl^e should sympathize with the views of\nsocialist as well as with the views of\nse opposed to Socialism. Yet we must\n:ountenance the advocates of revolu-r\nlary cnanxe wno in passionate riignts or\ntory decry present conditions and proe\nto substitute in their stead a state\ned on undemocratic principles; so, too.\njt we discountenance the advocate of\nression and reaction. Radical and reonlst\nalike should find little sympathy\nipproval with the public.\n7e must beware of the pessimist and\nmist such' as Basil Manly, who writes\nhe Nation of June, 1919: \"We are about\njnter a period of the most acute indus1\ntinrest and the most bitter industrial\ntroversy that the American nation has\nr known. Unless effective steps are\n;n we are certain to see within\nnext year strikes and mass movements\nabor beside which all previous American\nkes will pale into insignificance.\" So also\nit we be wary of tl\\e optimist who proma\nspeedy return to prosperity and\nmises happiness for all. We must face\nproblems squarely and work hard, so\nt the predictions of the pessimist will not\nborne out and so that we can hops to\n1 that which the optimist promises.\net us hope that a new era has been end\nupon In which all claaaes of society\ne come to a full realization that they\ne much In common and that by cooperathey\ncan each gain what they can\nttmately desire. L?et us hope that the\nprlcan nation has learned by Its experl9\nduring the late war that cooperation\nhe keynote to the answers to all our\n11c questions, whether they be Industrial,\nernmental, economfc or social. With coration\na (treat deal can be accomplished;\ntout It hut little can be accomplished,\nfhen the American people apply that\nch la urged here, then\" and only then\nwe have the true spirit that should preWe\nmay have lulls In our troubles,\npromises may he effected; but not uhtll\nare ready to carry out the foregoing\nc suggestions, not until we substitute\nnony for discord and cooperation for dlsed\neffort?then, and not before then, will\nhave as permanent, as enduring;, as everlng\na domestic peace aa can reasonably\nhoped for.\nfi","height":"22803","width":"16992"}}
